 The price of the small basket of tomatoes which was selling at N2200 last week, has risen to N2500 at Mile 12 market.
The rising price of the produce according to traders is not unconnected to the gradual return of the rainy season. Tomatoes is farmed mainly during the dry season in the Northern part of Nigeria.
However, consumers have expressed happiness over the stable price of beans, saying the price has not changed since February. They also said that the price of rice which rose by over 15 per cent during the Christmas and New Year celebration has also stablised at N17, 000 a 50 kilogramme bag few days to the end to the first quarter of 2019.
However, Sunday Telegraph learnt that the locally produced rice has remained scarce in most of the markets, even though the Federal Government has continued to blame smugglers for the poor insufficiency of the produce in the markets.
Survey of the prices of goods at Mile 12 and the Sabo markets, Ikorodu on Thursday, indicate that the prices of rice and beans have stablised in the markets. According to Mrs. Ronke Malik, a trader in the market, the demand for rice and beans has remained high in the market, attributing it to the stability in their prices. She said: “At this time of the year, the price of rice and beans crash, but what we are experiencing is stability in the old high prices, but the price is manageable and favourable to both the buyers and sellers. Mama Gold, one of the best premium rice sells from between N17000 to 17500 for 50kg. Compared to the prices same period in 2018, the difference is over N2, 000.  “The difference is too much for us the retailers and the buyers will always complain about the price before buying which is not good for the business.”
Beans remained stable with the different species going at different prices. Oloyin Beans (50kg) – N30,000 – N39,000 (depending on the market)Oloyin (25kg) – N15,000 – N19,000; Olotun (50kg) – N29,000 – N36,000, Olotun (25kg) – N14,000 – N17,500.
Meanwhile, at the Garage Market, Mrs. Elele, said that the price of noodles is stable. According to her, a carton of Indomie Noodles (small size) sells for N2100. Also, a consumer spoken to at the Alaba Rago Market on Thursday, expressed happiness over what he described as the low price of beans, saying compared to the price in fourth quarter of 2018, N300 a Derica cup, the price is good now at N200 a Derica cup.
Speaking, Iya Tolani said that at the Alaba Rago Market, predominantly populated by Northerners in Lagos State, the price of beans has continued to come down, they still expect it to further come down at to what it was sold in first three quarter of 2018, N150 a Derica cup.
She however expressed happiness the fall in the price beans and even rice, saying it will be good if it can fall to the 2018 prices.
Alhaji Baba Usman, a dealer in several foodstuffs in the market, including rice, beans, garri, semovita and food condiments, disclosed that the people coming to buy rice and beans are many, “We are however hoping that the prices will continue to fall so that sales will rise as it used to be.”